<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06323027 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06323027 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  Sandamp;L; LOAN; BANK; COMPANY; OFFICIAL; COURT; TRIAL; FRAUD; JURY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Jurors today began deliberating the fate of Charles Keating Jr., the formerLincoln Savings andamp; Loan owner accused of duping small investors into buyingjunk bonds at Lincoln branches.;   Keating stared soberly across the court atthe eight-woman, four-man jury as Superior Court Judge Lance A. Ito spent anhour instructing them on the laws they must follow.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  KEATING JURORS OPEN DELIBERATIONS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Ito said he believed it would take jurors at least two days merely to readtheir way through the various exhibits.;   Keating, 67, faces up to 10 yearsin prison if convicted of six or more charges.;   He is accused of 18 countsof failing to pass down information about the deteriorating financialcondition of Lincoln and its parent company, American Continental Corp. ACC,of Phoenix, bought the Irvine-based thrift in 1984.;   Lincoln investors wereamong thousands of American Continental bondholders whose investments becameworthless when Lincoln was seized and American Continental filed forbankruptcy protection in April 1989.;   Regulators said Lincoln's collapsecost taxpayers $2.6 billion, the most expensive thrift collapse in history.Holders of ACC bonds lost a total of $250 million.;   Deputy District AttorneyWilliam Hodgman argued at trial that buyers of high-risk, high-yield bondswere never told of operating losses at ACC, or of regulators' warnings thatLincoln was failing its net worth requirement.;   &quot;I feel pretty good,&quot;Hodgman said outside court today. &quot;I feel a little more anxious about thiscase than some others, because of the notoriety of it.&quot;;   Keating's attorney,Stephen C. Neal, maintained that lawyers, not his client, set up andsupervised the bond sales program. He said regulators repeatedly had approvedthe sales, and said disclosures about Keating's companies were made in bondprospectuses and other documents that were supposed to be given to prospectivebuyers.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Los Angeles  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911118  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  298  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday, November 18, 199100323027,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>